This was actually a trick question. There is no right answer. It is a complete 3-way guess as to whether you should continue with the @CQ, @C10, or a small club.

Your play will not matter if clubs are either 3-3 or 5-1, or if one of the defenders was dealt @CKJ9x. All that matters are the distributions in which one of the defenders was dealt either @CKx, @CJx, or @C9x. Each of these three layouts is equally likely. Each of the 3 possible plays will pick up clubs in 2 of the 3 layouts.

|cs|1|at|^-{ Playing the @CQ will succeed when a defender was dealt @CJx or @C9x, 
 but will fail when a defender was dealt @CKx. }

|cs|4|at|{ Playing the @C10 will succeed when a defender was dealt @CKx or @C9x, 
 but will fail when a defender was dealt @CJx. }

|cs|2|at|{ Playing a small club will succeed when a defender was dealt @CKx or @CJx, 
 but will fail when a defender was dealt @C9x. }
^-
Sorry if you feel ripped off by this trick question. We found this problem interesting because we think that a pure 3-way guess is a very rare thing in the game of bridge.

